cases of dengue, this year, only
one in the
area that we are treating.

21:58.150 --> 22:03.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Mosquitoes
killing mosquitoes.
It may sound too good to be
true, and despite

22:03.222 --> 22:09.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more than a decade of work, it
remains unclear
if this can have lasting impact
on a bigger

22:09.428 --> 22:14.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
scale. It's a high-tech twist in
the long,
difficult war to stop the spread
of diseases

22:14.867 --> 22:19.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
carried by the mosquito species
called Aedes
aegypti.

22:19.939 --> 22:21.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have been battling the same
enemy for generations.

22:21.941 --> 22:27.546 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NARRATOR: Notice the
white-tipped palps, the
triangular white spots on the
abdomen, the

22:27.580 --> 22:33.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
white leg bands, and the white
flyer shaped
design on the thorax. These are
characteristic

22:33.519 --> 22:35.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the adult aegypti mosquito.

22:35.387 --> 22:41.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Aegypti is blamed
for spreading
Zika virus, as well as dengue,
West Nile and

22:41.493 --> 22:47.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
yellow fever. Combined, the
diseases infect
hundreds of millions of people a
year, causing

22:47.166 --> 22:51.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a host of maladies and birth
defects, killing
several million.

22:51.837 --> 22:59.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But with Zika, there is growing
concern here
that other species are guilty as
well. In

22:59.111 --> 23:04.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this government lab in Recife,
Brazil, they
are working to develop a test
that can tell

23:04.149 --> 23:06.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if a mosquito is carrying Zika
virus.

23:06.619 --> 23:11.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right now, no one knows for
certain how common
it is, or in which species.

23:11.724 --> 23:14.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Marcelo Paiva is a molecular
entomologist.

23:14.760 --> 23:19.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, when compare this
against dengue
or yellow fever, any number of
other viruses

23:19.298 --> 23:21.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
borne by mosquitoes, we don't
know so much
about Zika, do we?

23:21.800 --> 23:22.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MARCELO PAIVA, Molecular
Entomologist: We
have no idea, actually.

23:22.868 --> 23:23.702 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Really? Tell me.

23:23.736 --> 23:25.204 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCELO PAIVA: This is totally
new.

23:25.237 --> 23:27.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's kind of --
well, it's
virgin science.

23:27.906 --> 23:34.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCELO PAIVA: It is, yes. We
were in a dark
field, now -- no light at end of
tunnel. Now

23:34.346 --> 23:36.482 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we're trying to clarify things.

23:36.515 --> 23:42.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: As they try to
solve this complex
puzzle, his boss, entomologist
Constancia

23:42.988 --> 23:48.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ayres, is trying to prove a
theory that would
have huge, global implications,
that another

23:48.827 --> 23:54.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mosquito species called Culex
quinquefasciatus
could also be a so-called vector
for Zika.

23:54.833 --> 24:02.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Culex is 20 times more abundant
here in Brazil,
and is also much more common
than Aedis aegypti

24:02.241 --> 24:04.043 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in North America and Europe.

24:04.076 --> 24:08.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CONSTANCIA AYRES, Entomologist:
In Micronesia,
when we had the first outbreak
of the Zika

24:08.280 --> 24:14.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in 2007, there is no Aedes
aegypti there.
So, probably, another vector was
transmitting

24:14.787 --> 24:23.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the disease. And Culex also
transmitted other
arbovirus, such as West Nile
virus, Japanese

24:23.429 --> 24:25.297 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
encephalitis, so why not Zika?

24:25.331 --> 24:30.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The two breeds
behave very
differently. Culex bites at
night, while aegypti

24:30.569 --> 24:36.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prefers the day. Culex breeds in
dirty water.
Aegypti likes her water clean.
This would

24:36.508 --> 24:40.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
dramatically up the ante for
traditional mosquito
control techniques.

24:40.279 --> 24:45.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CONSTANCIA AYRES: So, if both
species are
involved, you will have to use
repellent 24

24:45.651 --> 24:46.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
hours a day, basically.

24:46.985 --> 24:48.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Wow. Yes. So
you're going deet
all the time.

24:48.987 --> 24:50.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CONSTANCIA AYRES: Yes, all the
time.

24:50.789 --> 24:53.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: That's not good.
That's an
important, a significant thing.
It's a 24-hour

24:54.026 --> 24:55.761 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fight.

24:55.794 --> 24:59.598 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They are infecting Culex
mosquitoes with Zika
in the lab, then dissecting them
to see how

24:59.631 --> 25:05.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they carry and transmit the
virus. The jury
is still out on what happens in
the real world.

25:05.571 --> 25:10.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It could mean there will be
demand for another
breed of weaponized mosquito.

25:10.275 --> 25:14.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This not a new battle here in
Brazil. As a
matter of fact, it's actually a
long war.

25:14.279 --> 25:19.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they have had some success
over the years.
In the mid-'50s and the
mid-'70s, they very

25:19.385 --> 25:24.156 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
nearly eradicated these
mosquitoes using pesticides,
many of them DDT.

25:24.189 --> 25:30.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But even before DDT was banned,
though, the
mosquitoes developed a
resistance to it. So,

25:30.195 --> 25:35.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
today, with the population of
humans and mosquitoes
so much greater than ever, there
really is

25:35.467 --> 25:38.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
no realistic way to think about
eradication.

25:38.637 --> 25:44.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But scientists all over the
world are not
ready to surrender. Leslie
Vosshall is a professor

25:44.810 --> 25:47.980 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of neurogenetics at the
Rockefeller University
in New York.

25:48.013 --> 25:50.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLIE VOSSHALL, Rockefeller
University: So
we're trying to figure out why
some people

25:50.282 --> 25:53.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are more attractive than others.
The diseases
start with a mosquito. The
mosquito needs

25:53.886 --> 25:57.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to find someone to bite. The
more attractive
people are bitten more. We want
to understand

25:57.723 --> 25:59.491 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
why that is.

25:59.525 --> 26:03.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: She and her team
performed
what they all the mosquito
magnet study. Open

26:03.262 --> 26:09.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the gate, and down the chute
they go. Turns
out mosquitoes love some of us
more than others.

26:09.468 --> 26:11.236 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So what is the differentiator?

26:11.270 --> 26:15.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLIE VOSSHALL: So, mosquitoes,
especially
the mosquitoes that are
spreading Zika, dengue,

26:15.441 --> 26:20.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
chikungunya, they love humans
over any other
animal. So they're cuing into
our body odor,

26:20.946 --> 26:26.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the carbon dioxide in our
breath, our body
heat. So, it's the body odor
that I think

26:26.785 --> 26:30.656 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is what distinguishes us from
other non-human
animals.

26:30.689 --> 26:36.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Vosshall and her
team are creating
designer mosquitoes. It's
genetic engineering,

26:36.328 --> 26:39.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but a different version from
Oxitec's self-destructing
insects.

26:39.798 --> 26:45.637 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Here, they create unique
attributes, for example,
a bug that can't detect certain
odors, to

26:45.671 --> 26:47.573 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
try and understand what they are
hunting.

26:47.606 --> 26:51.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLIE VOSSHALL: Obviously, if
we figure out
what makes a mosquito magnet
attractive, then

26:51.710 --> 26:57.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we have understood a big part of
what mosquitoes
are hunting. Then we can
interrupt their hunting

26:57.282 --> 26:59.051 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
behavior.

26:59.084 --> 27:02.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In the meantime,
all we really
have are nets and deet.
Researchers aren't

27:02.855 --> 27:06.592 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
even sure how the chemical
thwarts mosquitoes.

27:06.625 --> 27:08.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Can't science do better?

27:08.360 --> 27:11.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LESLIE VOSSHALL: Ultimately, how
cool would
it be to have like a cream that
you put on

27:11.897 --> 27:18.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
your arm that has a probiotic,
right, that
makes you demagnetized as a
mosquito magnet?

27:18.203 --> 27:23.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But, for now,
there is little
to stop the global health havoc
caused by

27:23.175 --> 27:29.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mosquitoes. Zika and birth
defects are just
part of the devastation. The
most deadly animal

27:29.648 --> 27:36.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on Earth is an easy foe to
underestimate and
it marches on with impunity.

27:36.555 --> 27:46.265 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
