A new memoir captures the grief
of losing
a spouse and reassessing one's
path.

42:26.377 --> 42:30.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has this latest
addition to
the "NewsHour" Bookshelf.

42:30.648 --> 42:37.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For more than 35
years, radio
host Diane Rehm has tackled
pretty much every

42:37.455 --> 42:39.023 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
topic under the sun.

42:39.056 --> 42:42.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE REHM, Author, "On My Own":
Already,
hundreds of Syrians have been
killed.

42:42.894 --> 42:49.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Her two-hour
daily public radio
program produced by WMAU in
Washington, D.C.,

42:49.734 --> 42:53.337 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
reaches some 2.5 million
listeners nationwide.

42:53.371 --> 42:59.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now in a new book titled "On My
Own," she's
addressing a more personal an
raw topic, the

42:59.277 --> 43:05.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
death of her husband John after
54 years of
marriage. John was dying owed
with Parkinson's

43:05.249 --> 43:11.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
disease in 2005 and moved into
an assisted
living facility in 2012.

43:11.122 --> 43:16.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two years later, in steady
decline, he decided
to end his life. But with
doctors legally

43:16.461 --> 43:21.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
barred from assisting, his only
option was
to refuse food, liquids and
medication. His

43:21.799 --> 43:28.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
death came 10 days later. Diane
Rehm lives
alone now with her dog Maxie and
with lingering

43:28.372 --> 43:31.375 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
grief and anger over her
husband's last days.

43:31.409 --> 43:40.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE REHM: I so resented that
John was having
to go through this long 10-day
process to

43:40.318 --> 43:50.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
die. He had said 10 days earlier
he was ready
to die, and it took him that
long. It shouldn't

43:50.127 --> 43:53.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have, I don't believe, taken him
that long.

43:53.831 --> 43:58.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You write: "I
rage at a system
that wouldn't allow John to be
helped toward

43:58.069 --> 43:59.804 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his own death."

43:59.837 --> 44:03.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He knew what he was going
through. You two
had talked this through, and he
just wanted

44:03.908 --> 44:05.576 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to let it happen.

44:05.610 --> 44:15.119 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DIANE REHM: He wanted to
relinquish life.
He didn't commit suicide. He
wanted to let

44:15.152 --> 44:19.056 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
go of life and be on to the next
journey.

44:19.090 --> 44:22.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You and he had
talked a lot
about these kind of end-of-life
matters. Right?

44:22.927 --> 44:24.762 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DIANE REHM: Absolutely.

44:24.795 --> 44:27.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That is one of
the things that
comes through in the book, is
that that helped

44:27.932 --> 44:32.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you in some degree. Right? Even
as hard as
it was, you had talked it
through.

44:32.803 --> 44:42.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE REHM: Even after he said,
I'm ready,
I'm ready to die, I said to him,
sweetheart,

44:42.647 --> 44:47.184 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are you sure? Is this really
what you want?

44:47.218 --> 44:56.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said, absolutely. I can
no longer use
my hands. I cannot walk. I
cannot feed myself.

44:56.928 --> 45:02.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I cannot do anything for myself.
I am ready
to die.

45:02.667 --> 45:06.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One of the things
I'm sure
will resonate with a lot of
people, you refer

45:06.203 --> 45:12.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to is the capital-G guilt that
you felt along
the way, right, as you were
moving toward

45:12.343 --> 45:12.977 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this point.

45:13.010 --> 45:13.678 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

45:13.711 --> 45:14.478 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: ... the guilt?

45:14.512 --> 45:15.012 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DIANE REHM: Of course, of
course.

45:15.046 --> 45:16.714 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

45:16.747 --> 45:29.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE REHM: How could I not feel
guilt? I
think every spouse who sees
another go into

45:29.193 --> 45:34.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an assisted living facility must
experience
some of that.

45:34.599 --> 45:43.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If I had stayed home, if I had
given up my
work, if I had cared for him
here at home,

45:43.808 --> 45:51.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
perhaps he would have lived at
least a few
months longer. I'm not sure that
is the case.

45:51.282 --> 46:00.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it was the guilt I felt. We
take vows
when we marry, for better, for
worse, in sickness,

46:00.391 --> 46:02.259 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in health.

46:02.293 --> 46:06.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Fifty-four-year
marriage, right,
which you write about very
honestly. You write

46:06.430 --> 46:13.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about periods of joy and of
partnership, certainly,
but also, as you say, years of
hostility,

46:13.170 --> 46:16.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
endless periods of silence. Why
did you write
about that?

46:16.641 --> 46:24.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIANE REHM: Because I believe
that no marriage
is perfect.

46:24.281 --> 46:34.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And yet so many of us go into
marriage or
partnership or relationship
believing that

46:34.158 --> 46:41.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all is going to be sunny, all is
going to
be wonderful. I wish, Jeff, I
had been more

46:41.966 --> 46:50.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mature, because John needed more
distance
than I did. John needed more
quiet time than

46:50.841 --> 46:58.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I did. I love to be with people.
John's greatest
solace was being alone.

46:58.282 --> 47:02.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, in the end,
in his last
days, was there a kind of
understanding?

47:03.020 --> 47:05.056 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DIANE REHM: Totally.

47:05.089 --> 47:15.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, there was such closeness
in those
last three weeks, four weeks
before he died.

47:15.099 --> 47:21.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You know, out of
this experience,
you have become a much more
active advocate,

47:21.072 --> 47:25.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I guess, right, for the right to
die. That
sets you in the middle of a very
passionate

47:25.976 --> 47:26.811 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
debate in this country.

47:26.844 --> 47:29.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DIANE REHM: I appreciate both
sides.

47:29.914 --> 47:40.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I am arguing not that everyone
should feel
as I do and ask for death when
the time comes.

47:40.991 --> 47:52.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I understand those who would
prefer to give
and receive palliative care.
Total individual

47:52.036 --> 48:01.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
choice. But do not let the law
prevent me
from making my choice about my
own life.

48:01.145 --> 48:05.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Becoming so
public about it
also brought you some questions
and criticism

48:05.983 --> 48:07.017 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from your organization, right?

48:07.051 --> 48:08.886 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DIANE REHM: Exactly.

48:08.919 --> 48:12.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Whether you are
now an advocate
or your more traditional role as
a journalist,

48:12.790 --> 48:14.592 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
right?

48:14.625 --> 48:22.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE REHM: Once I leave the
microphone, then
I will become, as you say, an
advocate. Right

48:22.800 --> 48:33.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now, I am advocating for myself.
I am not
advocating for any organization
in particular

48:33.778 --> 48:42.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or any change in any state law
in particular.
I am advocating for myself.

48:42.153 --> 48:45.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, you're now,
as the book
says, on your own...

48:45.489 --> 48:46.891 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
DIANE REHM: Yes.

48:46.924 --> 48:48.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: ... for the first
time in many,
many, many years, right?

48:48.325 --> 48:49.293 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DIANE REHM: Yes, all my life.

48:49.326 --> 48:50.594 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Except for Maxie.

48:50.628 --> 48:55.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIANE REHM: Except for Maxie,
who is my constant
companion.

48:55.866 --> 49:01.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I talk to Maxie. I talk to John,
and John
talks back to me.

49:01.972 --> 49:04.742 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes. That
conversation hasn't
stopped, huh?

49:04.775 --> 49:10.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE REHM: It hasn't stopped. I
don't think
it will stop. And it really
helps me.

49:10.748 --> 49:15.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You have also
announced that
you will stop doing your radio
program at

49:15.085 --> 49:15.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the end of this year.

49:15.953 --> 49:17.054 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DIANE REHM: At the end of the
year.

49:17.087 --> 49:19.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I wonder if --
